----
Topic:: Examine to what extent affirmative action is a qualification over equality of opportunity
Date:: 2022-11-23
Course:: [[UPSC/PSIR\|PSIR]] 

----
>[! error] Introduction 
>Affirmative action is a public policy which accords special concession to to those who are deprived of adequate opportunity. It is meant for injustice that was meted to them in past.  


>[!done] Body 
> The debate of  'reverse discrimination' 
> Views of opponent of affirmative action 
> In India - [[Indra Sawhney Case\|Indra Sawhney Case]] - Creamy layer
> 

If principle of equality is interpreted to concede discrimination in favor of some deprived section, this issue has given rise to debate of reverse discrimination. 
It simply means favored treatment is given to 'hitherto deprived sections' , others are complaining on the ground that they are deprived of equality of opportunities.
It is argued that equality means 'removal of discrimination', there is no justification for turning the existing discriminatory practice in reverse direction. 

Supporter of Affirmative action argue that since some section of population were deprived of opportunities for their development in past, they should now be compensated. That it will fulfil the objective of equality. 
There is scarcity of opportunities of advancement, hence it not should always be on merit but also on need. That they should be given preferential treatment. 

Opponent of affirmative action argue that equality in society can only be applied in 'equality of opportunity' and not 'equality of opportunity'. As it would mean the merit is not respected, which is foundation of social stability and progress. 
They also argue that what happened in past was not their fault, and to penalize them for it is 'tantamount to departure from substantive justice'
 

>[!tip] Conclusion 
> Supreme Court of India in 1992 in  [[Indra Sawhney Case\|Indra Sawhney Case]] brought the concept of creamy layer and capped the percent of reservation to 50% otherwise it would be reverse discrimination.  This question demands very cautious solution.
